    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "When you say \"I'd like to support Node 10 if possible\" you are referring to having the build work (dev dependencies) for Node 10.\r\n\r\nThe test cases here are arguably more valuable here than the Solidity code. And test cases and code are indeed both part of the \"package\" here and in other software projects.\r\n\r\nAdding Node 10, 14, ... to a build matrix will NOT slow down build times because they run in parallel. (They will add billable minutes to your GitHub account, if that is worth discussing.)\r\n\r\nYou say \"I'd like to support Node 10 if possible\", which I agree is a good idea. I think the best way to get that is to put it in the matrix. Then contributors will know that you would like Node 10 support rather than having to search through the issues to learn this obscure fact from your-and-my conversation. In this way you will speed up the contribution process.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThen when you no longer want to support Node 10, because it is not possible... you accept a one-line change. And everybody that is interested in this will see the change in the expected place.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nBy \"supporting\" builds in 10, 14, ... and putting them in the matrix, everybody will see the warnings which apply only to some versions. Somebody should go fix each of these warnings. And by putting 14 in the matrix now (as a can-fail) you highlight some issues that other people can fix now (whether here or upstream). By the time OZC switches to a new Node version perhaps it will build without warnings from the get-go.",
